{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For each pair (m,n) that satisfies the conditions of the problem we have that f(f(n))=f(m)=n. Similarly f(f(m))=m. Also, if f(f(n))=n then n can be in a pair, namely (n,f(n)) or (f(n),n), whiever satisfies the conditions of the question. Now since f(f(n))-n cannot be the zero polynomial, it must be a polynomial of degree 200 with integer coefficients. Therefore these n are eligible to be in a pair. But, the question says that n<m, so n cannot equal f(n). So since f(n)-n cannot be the zero polynomial, it must be a polynomial of degree 100 with integer coefficients. Therefore there are only 100 integers that are eligible to be in pairs. Since each pair contains two numbers and each number can only be in one pair there are at most 50 pairs that satisfy the conditions of the question."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}
